Come down to me. Before the war - we used to - one year I'd go up North, and the other years the other - my friend would come down to me, and then we'd usually - off somewhere in
 the South of England, just for a week or ten days and - you know, see the South and when I went up there we used to - she actually didn't live in the Lakes, she lived at Barrow-in-Furness but we used to go up and have a week or ten days up in the Lakes s
omewhere, Keswick or Borrowdale or - Conniston or various places that we stayed up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you continue to do any cycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes, I cycled for the - the first year I was at Praze, I cycled to and for all that winter. Oh well - this - if this is 
teaching I - I've had enough already. Anyway in the spring I bought - a motor bike, and - I used to go to and for on my motor bike. I think people along the road used to - set their watches by me every morning, and I had some fun with that bike. First one
 
was a belt rid - belt drive, belt used to keep breaking, and then I'd be stranded and then I've been - towed home behind a - a - another bike and I've been towed home behind a car. Another time I came home on a lorry, they put the bike up - the bike broke
 down, they put the bike on the lorry and - I came home on that, astride my bicycle to keep it upright. Another time I drop - lifted the bike over there an came home on a fish cart. Yes. Then in 1934 I had ka car, and - I - got rid the bike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 At what stage did you begin to take an interest in the Red Cross?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Oh, soon after I came out of college. Yes, it must have been - it was before - just before dad died. He died in November '25 and I - it must been - the end of 1924, the beginning of '25 I started, and I was in the Red Cross for -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743  forty years, in various capaci}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
ties. Finished up as Divisional Director of the East Penwood division. And - well did - you know, enjoyed the work, until I began to feel a bit - the weight of the years were pressing. I'm still connected with Red Cross now. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you have any other special friends beside your college friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh - yes, I've got great friends here - Camborne. Lot's of of them I'm glad to say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 When you first left school did your parents wish to know then where you were going and what time you had to be home or anything like that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
I never remember asking them 'cos I - I - I used to tell them where I was going when I went out. There was no question. They usually knew where I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 At the grammar school could you tell me what age you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well I went to - I went to the grammar school at twelve. In - in September 1914.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 And you had a move then shortly afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes. Shortly after that was I - I - father was - he was
 in the Army, stationed at Newquay, we went up there thinking we were there for the winter and we were only up there a matter of a week or two and we were back in Camborne again, 'cos he had to go to Northumberland, so - I was - well I can't say I was sor
ry that I was - sorry from my point of view because I hated - the change to the school where I didn't know anybody and I was a bit of a - didn't like - you know I wasn't a very good mixer at that age, so - but - that only lasted a - few weeks, at Newquay.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 The grammar school was called the Country school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Country school. Yes, the Country school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did it take any other pupils but your age group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes, I think you could - they - they could - paying you see, there were a number of - of the
 pupils were paying pupils, I was a - scholarship child, but there were a number who paid and I think then there was no - I think they could come in at - I don't say - at a very advanced age but they could come in, they weren't - and of course there was a
 kindergarten - in the lower school as well. There was a kindergarten there then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 What age children went to the kindergarten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh I suppose children - six, seven, that sort of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 To junior?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes. Yes. Yes, they had all age children there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you like it at this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Oh yes, I - of course I - I knew everybody and we were - I enjoyed it, I loved it at school, I was very - always - in those days I was always sorry when Friday afternoons came. I was - I've just remember i
n 19 - this spring of 1915 - I was ill for - a while, I had - an enlarged heart and I was home from school for - oh quite a - quite a time, I - I was in bed for a fortnight I remember and lying on a - settee for another fortnight and - and I suppose I - I
 can't remember exactly how long I was home from school but I - was - that - in that spring, I remember that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did that set you back with your work or did they send you work at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 I think I - I - I don't - I can't remember whether I had wor
k sent home but - I don't remember being sort of very - much behind the others, I don't - you know, it doesn't stick out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Have you any idea how many of the children would have been scholarship pupils compared to the fee payers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 No, I - I really 
don't, I should - oh perhaps - difficult to say, I can't remember but - quite a number were fee paying pupils in the form I was in. I - don't - know whether it was fifty per cent or not but - there would be quite a number of fee payers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Do you remember if the teachers singled out some children for different treatment from others at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
No, I don't think so. No, I - course we - we all had our special favourites and among the staff and - we had - every summer term, we had a form picnic and
 we used to go to - usually we went to - Hayle, then walked across - went across the ferry at Hayle River you know, over the Links to Carbis Bay and had a picnic there. And you asked your three - you asked your form teacher of course went with you, and - 
I think we had - asked - two or three others, other - other start but we - we particularly wanted to go with the class. Sometimes you got your - you got your first choice and sometimes you didn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 How did you go, by train?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Train to Hayle, yes. And then - walked. And it was very - always a - quite a - a day that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did all the children at that school come from the same types of home or were some different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well - there were - there were I suppose - I think most - of the - well my frie
nd were all more or less the sort of - came from the sort of homes - home that I did some of them came from better homes no doubt, perhaps. Or - perhaps had more money. But - I don't remember a lot many that were - and yet some of them - must have been, d
o
 you remember a Mr Davies, Basset Road? He was head of Basset Road school. His daughter Dorothy, she - I remember she was in the top of the school when I was in the - in the middle, and the days when we used to - at the last day of the - term - usually th
e
 end of the school year, July - we youngsters always the last assembly when the older ones very often dissolved into tears because it was their last assembly - and we used to be, oh so and so, so and so, did you see so and so, she was crying. But - yes, o
f
 course he was headmaster of Basset Road, he would have had a much - higher standard of living that - that I should, than my father had you see. Though of course in those days the heads didn't have all that much money. Still they did have - he did have a 
house, and so on. School house in Basset Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Were there any with a lower standard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Yes, I think there were some quite poor ones. I think they got special - grants clothing and that sort of thing I think probably they were - helped, though of co
urse we didn't know it in those days. It wasn't made - public. Miss Pratt of course was the head in those days. Did you remember her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Miss Pratt did quite a lot of social work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 If anyone did anything that those teachers disapproved of what would happen, how would they punish the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
I don't know - oh lines and that sort of thing I think. That was the main - I - I was very law abiding, I didn't very often get punishment so I'm not really - re - don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did your parents ask you what you did at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Oh they were interested, and - of course the first - well we - they - dad used to try and help me with my homework sometimes if I needed any help, but - I don't - you know, they were - they were - 
quite - interested in my reports and all that sort of thing when they came in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did they ever visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well of course there were no PTA's then as there are now, so - oh I can't remember them - - I - mum used to go up and see Miss Pratt o
ccasionally about - anything but I don't know - my future possibly. I was - very keen on games, and played hockey and netball, tennis and - always - out for anything in that line. Played in the - in the teams, the school teams.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would your parents visit the school at speech days then, did they have such things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well - well the - you see, during the war - until 1918 - speech days were out, and - prizes were out, I got one miserable little certi}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743 f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 icate which I - I don't know what happened to it in the end, in l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743 i}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
eu of a prize, and after that - now - they didn't seem to come back, because I - I mean I was there - well - when did I tell you I - '21, well the speech days then hadn't come back to the grammar schools - the Country school then, and - and pri
zes - no prizes were given. I don't know when they started again, after my time anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 How old were you when you left that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well I was nineteen when I left - when I left - because I stayed on - to take metric, I didn't get metric though 
- through senior Cambridge. I took metric - in 19 - oh I can't remember, '20 I suppose. Anyway I - I got it - in the January of 1921, I'd had a term - I got fed up with school, and I took a term - with corres - a correspondence course and - got - took the
 
- took the - the exam in the January of 19 - 22, and - 1922, yes, I took it then and passed, and - the then I was home, well I was home before that time - that term working with the correspondence classes, but of course in those days if you - failed one s
ubject in metric you failed - you had to take the whole lot again, which - I felt very sore about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 What organisation was the correspondence course with, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 It was - one of the universities, Ox - no - no, it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743 couldn't have been, I've 
forgot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 ten the name of it now, it's such a long time ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 You would have to pay for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes. You paid for that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 That was while you were doing the little bit of teaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes. Well actually, I came home - I took it and - had to go to
 Plymouth to take it, now when I came - the - dad met me at the station when I came home and said that Mr Hayman had been in that day, wanted me to go to St Day on Monday, and I was going to relax I thought and - I had to - I went - no, not St Day, I thin
k that was when I went to East End, but I was only there a week. And - then I went to St Day later on, for a month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Going back to when you were at school at Penponds, we did talk about the children that you played with there and you said there was one 
particular child who was your own special friend. Could you tell me what her parents did, what was her home background?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh her father was a butcher, they lived next door to us. Her father was a butcher, and - I don't think - he - he - he didn't have 
a shop, I - I - I - he used to have a - stall in the market, do you remember when the Market House was a market or was that before your time? Yes, well they used to - Saturdays, Fridays and Saturdays I think they used to - have a stall in there, and I thi
nk he used to go - about, you know, take the meat round to people like they did in - carts, and - van - vans.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did they have other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes, they had quite - she was the youngest of - oh there were a number of boy and girls, they were - gr
own up - most of them, and there was one boy - who was more her age - just - a bit older than she was, but the others were most of them grown up and working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Can you remember any other families down at Penponds, you were saying that some weren't so we
ll off, perhaps they weren't so careful, can you remember any other who attened school at Penponds, what sort of conditions, what their parents did? Or why they shouldn't have been well off, were there any other reasons for not being well off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 No, I 
can't remember - more than the - I can't remember any in particular - any particular ones but of course there was the - always the - reason that possibly father}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 had gone abroad and - left mother with the children and then - faded out of the picture altoget
her and she had to - to get on as best she could with them. That so often happened in - Cornish families. When father went - went abroad - to work in the mines or somewhere, find - gold at the end of the rainbow which didn't very often materialize. And th
en the families were left to fend for themselves very often. But - I can't give you any particular - ones - like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 A lot of miners had to leave work early because of illness?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes, the - the miners tisis, yes. They often came - some very often came home from abroad with it too, and were unfit to work at all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 The neighbours you mentioned who were left in charge of your pheasants, what sort of job did they have, what sort of family were they?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 They were very nice people. He was - no
w am I right, I think I am - he used to work by the roadside cracking stones, I - I'm almost sure he did. He's been dead many years now. They were very nice, we were very fond of them. There was the two old - people, well the mother and father, they seeme
d
 old to me, they weren't all that old I suppose, and he couldn't read and I know during the war - he used to buy a paper, go to town, buy a paper and go into Mr Pearce who lived up the road, for him - he used to read it to him, read the war news, and - th
e
y had a daughter, she was a milliner and they had another daughter who was a cook in a family, you know, with a - in a - private family. There was - were there only two daughters? Those are the only ones I can remember, but - we liked the very much. They 
f
ollowed - you remember I told you about Mrs Mitchelly who was the teacher at Penponds when I went to school, I went to school with her, she took me to school, well - they'd moved, I don't know where they went, I can't remember, and - these people followed
 them, followed Mrs Mitchly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you recall any incidents of people poaching pheasants at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743 No, you see p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
heasants - that would happen over in Pendarves, that was some way away from us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 You never knew of any cases, or rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
You were saying that your father used to be away at two or three days a week and not home to lunch, on the days that his work was in Camborne, would he have been at home to lunch then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well his work - oh - you - he - you see, there was o
nly one day that he went to Hayle, that - that's his long day, that's was the only day he was out except on the - every alternate Friday when he went to the - board meeting at Redruth, an they had lunch in there, but the other days he was home every day. 
Because - when he did the Troon round that was only a - half day, you know, it didn't take him the whole day to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 So it was just the one day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Just the one day on the Wednesday and and alternate Fridays - when - he went for the board meeting, Board of Guardians meeting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 You were saying about the Guardians, can you recall any of them, what sort of occupations they had, what sort of backgrounds they came from?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh I know when - one - he was - he had been to a - had been abroad and m
ade his money - in Africa in the diamond mines in Kimberley and - he had a smallholding, built a nice house for himself, actually he was our landlord, he built the - three houses - in Barripper Road which are still there, and - called it Kimberley Terrace
, three houses, and - he was one of the Guardians.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did he have any family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Yes, he had a son and a daughter. They're both dead now. Of course he and his wife too. But - they were very kind. They had - they used - they had - one or two cows, they 
didn't - go in - mean - I mean they didn't keep - didn't try to keep a farm, but - they used to sell cream, we used to buy cream at four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 pence a - quarter, and - when my father was ill in 1916 every day Mrs Pearce made a - junket and sent it down to dad wi
th a crust of - clotted - beautiful yellow clotted cream on top. She never - she never missed. He was very very fond of it. They were very kind people. But - he was rather hard as a Guardian.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 What sort of way would they be hard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well I mean he w
asn't - I think I mentioned before that - they were - they didn't show a lot of milk of human kindness to people who were in poor positions - I know dad used to try and - get things for people that he - people that he thought deserved them, it didn't alwa
ys come off, the Guardians - you know, they were - rather on the stingy side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you know any others that formed the Guardians?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well I expect I did but I can't remember them, I mean as a child you see I was quite - young and I mean - it didn't m
ean much to me in those days. If I - as I say, if I were in teens I should probably have had more idea of what was going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would they have been t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 ought to have been in a higher social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes I suppose they would consider themselves so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Many people did divide society into different social classes or groups in those days, did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 No, I don't think so. I - if my parents did they didn't - sort of pass it on to me - as some
 parents used to I believe, I mean - some children weren't allowed to play with this one and that one because they weren't quite - quite as - up - far enough up the social scale, but I - well, possibly because I - There weren't many children around us, yo
u see I had this child from next door who was a friend, and - I had other friends, but not - there with me all the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would some be referred to as upper class, for example I suppose the Pendarves' would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh they would be looked upon as - upper class, yes. I suppose nowadays they'd be looked upon as upper middle class these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
The professional classes, like your father or schoolmasters or people like that, would they have been thought to have been a superior class than say labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 I think they were looked up to as sort of - well having a bit more education and knowing a bit more about things - in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 People would look to them for a lead?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 You mentioned when you were a child that mother was quite frequently engaged in sewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 She did a lot of sewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did she do any sewing for anyone else besides the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh no. No, only for - mainly for me and - for herself. Well my - and for dad sometimes, I can remember
 her making pyjamas and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did she knit socks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 I didn't ask you what your parents would have thought of swearing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well - they didn't - wouldn't - certainly wouldn't encourage it, I don't think. Well - I neve
r heard my father swear - except - he might say a damn sometimes or a - but it - you know, it wasn't a - he wasn't a - given to swearing. Like some, I don't know - perhaps some children nowadays - and you hear the language that's used to them well they -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 You mentioned that you went to church, which denomination was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Penponds - Church of England. I still go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did your parents attend that church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would you have thought that any of these people who were not so well off, could I ever be attributed to drink, was there much of that about?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
There were - there was a - a certain - I suppose there were a certain number of people who - drank, but - actually, the old chap next door - the - the butcher, he was a - a - he dr
ank all right and one night, we'd gone to bed I believe, I - I don't think I heard much about it, dad was called up, he'd been - he - he'd broken his leg, he'd been Helston Market, and the - broke - he - he - somebody had put him up in his trap, and the h
o
rse - the pony had brought him - or the horse brought him home, but - he - had a - he had a broken leg, dad with - a - other - I don't know who else, but - they found - all the men they could find 'cos he was a great big man, to - get him to bed. That - h
e used to drink. But - my - I didn't come into contact with - people who drank - anyway, not - knowlingly. I mean I didn't know about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Do you remember any very big families with a lot of children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well my mother had a - a distant cousin who had eleven children. She - they lived at Redruth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would some people perhaps have been hard put because of the size of their family
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh yes, yes very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 What sort of people would you say went to church and the chapel, was there any difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Well, or course the - in - the early days, when I was a child, a lot of people from Camborne used to go down to Penponds church. Quite - and people with - fair amount of money, but - the chapel of course was confined to people of the village. You woul
dn't get outside - well, outsiders coming to - to the chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 I wonder why Camborne people would have gone to Penponds church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well, in those days the vicar - who was - he later became Canon Carah - he was - very popular, and - lots of people wo
uld come down to Penponds, from Camborne for the - ordinary weekly services. Canon Carah was a - he was very keen - on - particularly on - old Cornwall, and he started the Old Cornwall Society with one or two others in Camborne when it began, that's a goo
d many - years ago now. He - he was very popular.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Can you remember any other episodes about your childhood, for example what your father said when you tore your coat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well he - he didn't - he didn't - actually say - I told him, I was going to be
d and he was to break the news and that was that, but - I can remember - I think that before that when I was even smaller, one day I had one of those - belts - round my dress - I don't know what they were, they weren't made in plastic in those days but th
e
y were made of something and somebody had caught hold of it and split it, and I was very upset about that and I told dad, and he said, well - has mum got any - cotton, any - anything like that colour? So I said, yes. So he said well you get it and a needl
e and cotton and we shut ourselves in the scullery while he mended my belt for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 He was practical?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did father ever go to a pub of an evening or attend pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Well I don't think he went to a pub to - spend a whole evening, he migh
t go in a have a drink with anybody - but he didn't have one special local like some - you know, like people do in these days and always go to the same one. I think in those days when the Commercial Hotel was open, you remember, by the - the fountain - he
 - would go in there occasionally or if he met somebody perhaps he hadn't seen for some time or - that sort of thing, but I - he didn't - oh I - he was - I - you asked about clubs, he - I - I didn't tell you he was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8259177\charrsid813743 Freemason}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 . That -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 He would attend the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8259177\charrsid813743 Freemasons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes, the banquets and so on that they - they set up themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would he go regularly to a pub or just occasionally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh just occasionally, I don't - he didn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would mother go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 No. No, she didn't go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you think in those days of some people as being rough and some as being respectable in your locality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 
Well you see - living - we lived - in a - a - a small terrace of houses, three houses - on - between Camborne and - the nearest village, which - was - 
three quarters of a mile away, so that I didn't see - how other people lived really very much, except the people who were on each side of us. I didn't get a - a really general picture of - of a village for instance. I - used to go to Penponds quite a lot 
-
 but I wasn't living there, and I only saw - when I went to Penponds I saw my own particular - our own particular friends who we went to see. But - no doubt there were - in the village, people of that - who would be counted as a bit rough in their - way o
f living.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you notice any difference in the children who attended Penponds school, would any of them come with poor footwear for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Oh sometimes, yes, sometimes they were - some of them were - poorly clothed, but most of us - I've got 
photographs now, at least I - I believe I have somewhere, groups taken, of - the classes in those days, we were all - with our pinafores on and so on, I've got one too when - I was in a very smart blue velvet - I know it was blue, it isn't - it's black an
d white photograph - a blue - a velvet dress, I felt very - I expect it was put on for the occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 You don't remember any children ever coming to school barefoot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Feet out on the ground some people used to say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes. Yes. Yes.
 I saw some nearly that - nearly like that when I was - teaching in that - that family I mentioned just now, that big family coming into Praze, they would have - had very poor foot - footwear. That was in - the early days when I was at Praze, started ther
e in 1924.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Would they he farm labourers children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3105192 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 Did you know any farm labourers around here when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1142424 LP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16601870\charrsid813743 No. No.
\par }}